    "summary": "The Council of Chalcedon (451 AD) was the fourth and most divisive of the Ecumenical Councils of early Christianity — a gathering of over 500 bishops convened by Emperor Marcian near Constantinople that defined the Chalcedonian formula: that Christ is 'one person in two natures, without confusion, without change, without division, without separation.' This formula was intended to resolve decades of Christological controversy between those who emphasized Christ's divine nature and those who emphasized the unity of his divine and human natures, but instead it permanently divided the Christian world.\n\nThe council's formula was accepted by the Roman and Byzantine imperial churches, creating what became 'Chalcedonian' Christianity — the common ancestor of Roman Catholicism, Eastern Orthodoxy, and Protestantism. But it was rejected by the Egyptian, Ethiopian, Armenian, Syriac, and much of the Eastern church, who maintained Miaphysite Christology and formed the 'Oriental Orthodox' churches ([[event:2104|Coptic Christianity]], Armenian Apostolic, Ethiopian Orthodox, Syriac Orthodox). These churches were consequently often persecuted by Byzantine imperial authorities, and their resentment of Constantinople contributed to the ease with which Arab Muslim forces conquered Egypt and Syria in the 7th century — populations that had been marginalized by Chalcedonian imperial Christianity showed little motivation to defend Byzantine rule. The Council of Chalcedon thus had long-term geopolitical consequences extending far beyond theology.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Council_of_Chalcedon",
